────────────────────────────────
NARRATIVE_SUMMARY:
Anchor stopped running. Not because the threat is gone—it isn't. Not because he's finally safe—he'll never be safe. He stopped running because he realized that running was never the point.
The Container of Fragments doesn't flee from broken things. It holds them.
At the Orpheus Lounge, he met Ilya's successor—a woman without a name. He placed 650,000¥ worth of art, data, and client lists on Table 7 and bought not just a fence, but a dynasty. She does not know his name. She knows his ambition. That was enough.
At Georgetown warehouse, he opened doors. Veld. Chen. Miriam. Each one walked through.
In Cold Storage Cell A-7, he found seven vacant racks and one [PENDING] placard with his name on it. Fragment 08. Seventeen years of waiting for a ghost who was never coming back.
Then he walked through Dr. Arisawa's door.
She asked if he brought the door or the ghost. He brought himself—not Subject 08, not Fragment 08, not the man who died in 2079. He brought Anchor. And he told her that seventeen years of guilt could not be deleted, but it could be shared.
She asked him her daughter's name. He didn't know it. But he asked her to say it anyway.
Yuki.
Seventeen years since she'd spoken it aloud.
Anchor took her termination logs and made them ash. He took her surveillance archives and made them silence. He took her commlink and made it a door.
And she walked through.
The ghost is done waiting. The Container holds one more fragment. The weight of everything he carries presses down, constant and patient, against the walls of the vessel that holds them.
He doesn't put it down.
He builds around it.
────────────────────────────────
